In 1953, African Americans living in Baton Rouge came together in an eight-day boycott to protest segregated seating on city buses.  The Baton Rouge Bus Boycott was the first bus boycott of the Civil Rights Movement & inspired countless others across the country. #BHM https://t.co/7KUOE8hhHS

Jazz musician Edgar “Dooky” Chase turned his parents small sandwich shop into a world-renowned restaurant and gathering place for Civil Rights leaders such as Thurgood Marshall, Martin Luther King, and A.P. Tureaud #BlackHistoryMonth https://t.co/C825PW4WD2

A.P. Tureaud, along with Thurgood Marshall and the @NAACP_LDF, filed and won the lawsuits that ended Jim Crow segregation in the Orleans Parish School System. #BlackHistoryMonth https://t.co/tZHX2VBmXS

Before becoming the first African-American woman to serve in the Louisiana House of Representatives, Dorothy Mae Taylor desegregated Mardi Gras while serving on the New Orleans City Council. #BlackHistoryMonth https://t.co/xqMJXJmoYr
